STEP 1 — Create a Firebase Project
  1.Go to https://console.firebase.google.com
  2.Sign in with your Google/Gmail account
  3.Click "Add project"
  4.Type a project name (example: school-lrn-app)
  5.Turn OFF Google Analytics (you don't need it)
  6.Click "Create project"
  7. Wait about 10 seconds for it to finish


STEP 2 — Register a Web App - After your project is created, you'll see the dashboard.
  1.Click the </> icon (this is the Web icon)
  2.Give your app a nickname (example: school-web)
  3.Leave "Firebase Hosting" unchecked
  4.Click "Register app"
  5.Firebase will show you a block of code that starts with:
          ________________________________________
          js   const firebaseConfig = { ... }    
          ________________________________________
                                                
  6.Copy this config — you will paste it into your HTML file


STEP 3 — Enable Email/Password Login
  1.In the left sidebar, click "Authentication"
  2.Click "Get started"
  3.Click "Sign-in method" tab
  4.Click "Email/Password"
  5.Toggle the FIRST switch to ON (blue)
  6.Leave the second switch (Email link) OFF
  7.Click "Save"
  8.This tells Firebase: "Yes, allow users to sign up with email and password."


STEP 4 — Create Firestore Database
  1.In the left sidebar, click "Firestore Database"
  2.Click "Create database"
  3.Choose "Start in test mode" (allows reading/writing for 30 days)
  4.Choose server location: asia-southeast1 (Singapore)
  5.Choose this if you are in the Philippines — it's the closest
  6.Click "Enable"
  7.Wait for it to finish — you'll see an empty database panel

STEP 5 — Set Firestore Security Rules
  1.Inside Firestore Database, click the "Rules" tab
  2.Replace everything with this:

____________________________________________

rules_version = '2';
service cloud.firestore {
  match /databases/{database}/documents {
    match /users/{userId} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null;
    }
  }
}

____________________________________________

  3.Click "Publish"
  What this rule means:
    - Only logged-in users can read or write data
    - People who are NOT logged in cannot touch the database


STEP 6 — Add Your Domain to Authorized List
  1,Because you are testing on your computer (localhost),
  2.Firebase needs to know your local address is safe.
  3.Go to Authentication → Settings tab
  4.Scroll down to "Authorized domains"
    - Click "Add domain"
    - Type: 127.0.0.1
    - Click "Add"
  5.This tells Firebase: "Trust requests coming from my computer."








